WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.200 --> 00:00:03.370
ROMAN NURIK: All right.

00:00:03.370 --> 00:00:05.490
Hello, everybody, and welcome
back to "Android Design in

00:00:05.490 --> 00:00:07.680
Action." My name
is Roman Nurik.

00:00:07.680 --> 00:00:09.475
And with me here today
is Adam Koch--

00:00:09.475 --> 00:00:09.770
ADAM KOCH: Hey, guys.

00:00:09.770 --> 00:00:11.511
ROMAN NURIK: --and
Nick Butcher.

00:00:11.511 --> 00:00:12.380
NICK BUTCHER: Hello.

00:00:12.380 --> 00:00:15.080
ROMAN NURIK: So today, we're
going to be talking about

00:00:15.080 --> 00:00:18.550
shopping list apps and the
contextual action bar.

00:00:18.550 --> 00:00:20.930
And before we jump in, I just
want to remind everybody what

00:00:20.930 --> 00:00:22.640
this show is all about.

00:00:22.640 --> 00:00:24.890
So on "Android Design in
Action," we take a look at

00:00:24.890 --> 00:00:27.570
apps that have been previously
reviewed on "The App Clinic,"

00:00:27.570 --> 00:00:29.040
which is on Fridays.

00:00:29.040 --> 00:00:31.990
And we take a look at how we
can improve some of the

00:00:31.990 --> 00:00:34.670
screens, some of the visual
designs in the screens of

00:00:34.670 --> 00:00:36.350
those apps.

00:00:36.350 --> 00:00:38.110
And then, more recently,
we've been diving

00:00:38.110 --> 00:00:39.940
into specific topics.

00:00:39.940 --> 00:00:43.090
For example, a few weeks ago,
we did responsive design,

00:00:43.090 --> 00:00:47.870
meaning designing for tablets
and phones and basically any

00:00:47.870 --> 00:00:50.860
screen size on a spectrum
of devices.

00:00:50.860 --> 00:00:53.340
And today, like I said, we're
going to be talking about the

00:00:53.340 --> 00:00:55.010
contextual action bar.

00:00:55.010 --> 00:01:00.300
So let's jump in with the very
first app that we'll look at

00:01:00.300 --> 00:01:04.480
which was reviewed last week on
"The App Clinic." And that

00:01:04.480 --> 00:01:07.640
app is Grocery IQ.

00:01:07.640 --> 00:01:10.310
So before we jump into the
redesign, let's talk about

00:01:10.310 --> 00:01:11.730
what this app does.

00:01:11.730 --> 00:01:15.040
And so this app basically lets
you manage a number of

00:01:15.040 --> 00:01:17.090
different lists, or
shopping lists.

00:01:17.090 --> 00:01:20.840
So let's say you have a favorite
bakery nearby or a

00:01:20.840 --> 00:01:23.530
favorite supermarket nearby.

00:01:23.530 --> 00:01:25.660
And you know that they sell
certain products.

00:01:25.660 --> 00:01:27.570
So what you can do is you can
actually create a shopping

00:01:27.570 --> 00:01:32.710
list and create or add items to
your list that are broken

00:01:32.710 --> 00:01:35.700
up by the different stores in
which you would buy them.

00:01:35.700 --> 00:01:38.680
So the bakery may have
breads and cereals

00:01:38.680 --> 00:01:40.120
and things like that.

00:01:40.120 --> 00:01:41.500
And the grocery store
or supermarket

00:01:41.500 --> 00:01:43.310
may have other things.

00:01:43.310 --> 00:01:45.890
So one of the key differences
between this app and other

00:01:45.890 --> 00:01:48.580
shopping list apps is the
ability to kind of break

00:01:48.580 --> 00:01:50.440
things up in that way.

00:01:50.440 --> 00:01:53.720
Also, it lets you-- let's just
zoom into the screens here.

00:01:53.720 --> 00:02:00.300
It lets you look at some
coupons for, I guess,

00:02:00.300 --> 00:02:03.260
different products that you
may want to buy, maybe

00:02:03.260 --> 00:02:05.830
contextually relevant or not.

00:02:05.830 --> 00:02:08.000
It lets you store favorites.

00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:10.120
It lets you do a lot of
different types of things.

00:02:10.120 --> 00:02:13.300
So it's basically a shopping
list that lets you neatly

00:02:13.300 --> 00:02:16.750
categorize your different items
and lets you also look

00:02:16.750 --> 00:02:18.150
at coupons as well.

00:02:18.150 --> 00:02:20.212
Before we jump in, have you
guys used this app at all?

00:02:20.212 --> 00:02:25.690
Or do you have any other
thoughts on the initial

00:02:25.690 --> 00:02:28.790
background on this app?

00:02:28.790 --> 00:02:29.510
NICK BUTCHER: No.

00:02:29.510 --> 00:02:29.820
ADAM KOCH: Not really.

00:02:29.820 --> 00:02:32.660
Actually, I did try it
a little while back.

00:02:32.660 --> 00:02:36.680
And unfortunately for me, when
I see the design looked kind

00:02:36.680 --> 00:02:39.355
of dated like this, I usually go
and just sort of uninstall

00:02:39.355 --> 00:02:40.050
it immediately.

00:02:40.050 --> 00:02:42.430
So I didn't get to try it out
too much, unfortunately.

00:02:42.430 --> 00:02:43.280
ROMAN NURIK: Yeah.

00:02:43.280 --> 00:02:47.060
And this app, to be fair, is
using some of the older

00:02:47.060 --> 00:02:48.940
patterns, some of the
Gingerbread styling with the

00:02:48.940 --> 00:02:50.580
tabs, actually.

00:02:50.580 --> 00:02:52.500
About a year or so ago,
they'd probably-- or

00:02:52.500 --> 00:02:53.970
maybe two years ago--

00:02:53.970 --> 00:02:56.990
those would be perfectly
normal tabs.

00:02:56.990 --> 00:02:59.410
They're actually using the
correct guidelines for the

00:02:59.410 --> 00:03:02.500
icons and so on and
so forth for tabs.

00:03:02.500 --> 00:03:04.090
But it's really just
kind of dated.

00:03:04.090 --> 00:03:05.700
That's exactly how I'd put it.

00:03:05.700 --> 00:03:08.985
ADAM KOCH: And then, of course,
the Menu button, the

00:03:08.985 --> 00:03:11.220
button of shame down the bottom
that the guys from "The

00:03:11.220 --> 00:03:12.430
App Clinic" mentioned as well.

00:03:12.430 --> 00:03:14.450
ROMAN NURIK: Yeah, the legacy
Menu button is something that

00:03:14.450 --> 00:03:15.510
should really just go away.

00:03:15.510 --> 00:03:18.710
And we have a solution
for that, anyway.

00:03:18.710 --> 00:03:21.900
And the other issue here is that
it's using some of the

00:03:21.900 --> 00:03:25.070
gradients that you'd find on
other platforms, kind of those

00:03:25.070 --> 00:03:27.980
stark gradients, and
also these kind of

00:03:27.980 --> 00:03:29.430
one-pixel text shadows.

00:03:29.430 --> 00:03:30.840
This is something we haven't
talked about

00:03:30.840 --> 00:03:31.500
before in this show.

00:03:31.500 --> 00:03:35.410
But another thing that
developers do a lot aside from

00:03:35.410 --> 00:03:38.020
gradients and things like that
is adding these tiny little

00:03:38.020 --> 00:03:42.530
shadows to kind of give a sense
of depth to your text.

00:03:42.530 --> 00:03:44.960
And in Android, that's
perfectly fine to do.

00:03:44.960 --> 00:03:48.010
You can do it in a lot of cases,
but oftentimes it's

00:03:48.010 --> 00:03:51.310
done without real thought
as to why.

00:03:51.310 --> 00:03:53.550
Is there a reason
for doing this?

00:03:53.550 --> 00:03:55.930
And I think, in this case, it
works fairly well because it's

00:03:55.930 --> 00:03:57.260
very subtle.

00:03:57.260 --> 00:04:02.360
But if you were to move over
to the Holo visual styling,

00:04:02.360 --> 00:04:06.290
the new modern Android UI look
and feel, you should try to

00:04:06.290 --> 00:04:11.420
avoid things like that, those
things that add a

00:04:11.420 --> 00:04:13.290
subtle sense of depth.

00:04:13.290 --> 00:04:14.690
It's almost unnecessary.

00:04:14.690 --> 00:04:16.839
But again, it's totally fine
if the rest of your visual

00:04:16.839 --> 00:04:20.019
design matches with that.

00:04:20.019 --> 00:04:22.710
And the other thing that
we like to point out is

00:04:22.710 --> 00:04:23.730
right-facing carets.

00:04:23.730 --> 00:04:27.430
Actually, on the screen,
touching the list items here

00:04:27.430 --> 00:04:29.410
doesn't really do anything.

00:04:29.410 --> 00:04:30.740
It actually does nothing.

00:04:30.740 --> 00:04:34.390
But to get into the details,
you actually have to touch

00:04:34.390 --> 00:04:36.790
this secondary action or
the secondary touch

00:04:36.790 --> 00:04:38.090
area on the list item.

00:04:38.090 --> 00:04:41.060
And then to check the item, you
just touch this check box.

00:04:41.060 --> 00:04:43.280
So some of these things
make sense, some

00:04:43.280 --> 00:04:45.100
of them not so much.

00:04:45.100 --> 00:04:47.330
So we wanted to kind of rethink
how you could approach

00:04:47.330 --> 00:04:50.240
this screen and this
app in general.

00:04:50.240 --> 00:04:53.600
So let's jump into the
redesign screen.

00:04:53.600 --> 00:04:54.860
Hopefully, let's get to 100%.

00:04:54.860 --> 00:04:55.950
OK.

00:04:55.950 --> 00:04:57.720
So let's jump into the
redesign screen.

00:04:57.720 --> 00:05:02.860
So as we always do, we've added
a proper action bar.

00:05:02.860 --> 00:05:07.180
We've added some iconography,
some branding on the top left.

00:05:07.180 --> 00:05:10.690
We added a single checkout
action button.

00:05:10.690 --> 00:05:14.860
And if you'll notice back here,
checkout is something

00:05:14.860 --> 00:05:19.440
that after you check the items
that you've purchased, you can

00:05:19.440 --> 00:05:20.180
press Checkout.

00:05:20.180 --> 00:05:23.480
And it moves those items into
your history, so that then

00:05:23.480 --> 00:05:25.900
next time you're shopping or
such, you can just bring

00:05:25.900 --> 00:05:28.410
things into your list directly
from your history.

00:05:28.410 --> 00:05:31.090
So it's kind of a neat
little feature.

00:05:31.090 --> 00:05:32.970
And we decided to move that
as a primary action

00:05:32.970 --> 00:05:34.520
in the action bar.

00:05:34.520 --> 00:05:37.510
We also added spinner navigation
at the top.

00:05:37.510 --> 00:05:40.370
And we'll show details
on that in a second.

00:05:40.370 --> 00:05:41.810
But basically, it lets
you switch between

00:05:41.810 --> 00:05:42.960
the different stores.

00:05:42.960 --> 00:05:44.870
And you'll see later, it lets
you manage stores and things

00:05:44.870 --> 00:05:46.570
like that, as well.

00:05:46.570 --> 00:05:53.250
And then, for the actual list
itself, we've presented the

00:05:53.250 --> 00:05:54.920
same old list.

00:05:54.920 --> 00:05:59.580
But to actually jump into the
details, you just touch once

00:05:59.580 --> 00:06:01.640
on the text here.

00:06:01.640 --> 00:06:05.050
And just as before, you can
check the box to the left to

00:06:05.050 --> 00:06:06.380
mark it as complete.

00:06:06.380 --> 00:06:09.620
But it doesn't actually move it
into a completely separate

00:06:09.620 --> 00:06:11.040
area once it's checked.

00:06:11.040 --> 00:06:14.310
It stays put, which is probably
a safer interaction,

00:06:14.310 --> 00:06:17.750
a more consistent interaction.

00:06:17.750 --> 00:06:19.420
The other thing I should mention
is that we've also

00:06:19.420 --> 00:06:20.770
brought up coupons.

00:06:20.770 --> 00:06:22.020
This is one thing I wanted
to talk about.

00:06:22.020 --> 00:06:25.440
And it seems like coupons in
this app-- and I think the

00:06:25.440 --> 00:06:27.130
developer is coupons.com--

00:06:27.130 --> 00:06:29.030
seems like coupons are a fairly
important part of

00:06:29.030 --> 00:06:32.640
either the business model, or
maybe it's revenue driving.

00:06:32.640 --> 00:06:33.140
I don't really know.

00:06:33.140 --> 00:06:35.690
But coupons seemed fairly
important, but they weren't

00:06:35.690 --> 00:06:36.820
immediately visible.

00:06:36.820 --> 00:06:39.780
So one way in which we tried to
bring that out more is to

00:06:39.780 --> 00:06:41.990
make it more contextually
relevant.

00:06:41.990 --> 00:06:46.790
So if there's a coupon for one
of the items in your list--

00:06:46.790 --> 00:06:50.820
let's say at a store nearby
there's a coupon for it--

00:06:50.820 --> 00:06:53.330
it'll show up as a secondary
action here with the number of

00:06:53.330 --> 00:06:54.270
coupons found.

00:06:54.270 --> 00:06:55.580
And then touching that
takes you to the

00:06:55.580 --> 00:06:57.840
coupon detail screen.

00:06:57.840 --> 00:07:03.620
And we also decided, why not
make coupons a secondary

00:07:03.620 --> 00:07:05.650
section at the bottom?

00:07:05.650 --> 00:07:07.170
Let's say I have
no list items.

00:07:07.170 --> 00:07:09.090
I have nothing on my
shopping list.

00:07:09.090 --> 00:07:10.380
Why not just show coupons?

00:07:10.380 --> 00:07:13.830
Hey, I forgot to get soup
the other week.

00:07:13.830 --> 00:07:14.960
And there's a coupon for soup.

00:07:14.960 --> 00:07:18.710
So let me just pop that
into my shopping list.

00:07:18.710 --> 00:07:22.030
But also, if you do have lots
of shopping list items, then

00:07:22.030 --> 00:07:24.730
you're probably not so much
worried about other products.

00:07:24.730 --> 00:07:26.840
You probably want to just get
rid of those products and buy

00:07:26.840 --> 00:07:29.210
those, and not worry about
anything else.

00:07:29.210 --> 00:07:31.750
And so coupons moves all the
way to the bottom of that.

00:07:31.750 --> 00:07:35.720
And then we used a different
visual indicator, this kind of

00:07:35.720 --> 00:07:38.950
almost faux torn edge.

00:07:38.950 --> 00:07:41.350
And this is borderline
skeuomorphic, but it doesn't

00:07:41.350 --> 00:07:42.570
really matter.

00:07:42.570 --> 00:07:48.520
It's this secondary part of the
screen that shows you that

00:07:48.520 --> 00:07:51.360
this is clearly a different
part of the app and a

00:07:51.360 --> 00:07:52.520
different set of items.

00:07:52.520 --> 00:07:56.440
So it's a clear visual
delineation.

00:07:56.440 --> 00:08:00.970
And then we've also used this
blue accent color throughout

00:08:00.970 --> 00:08:02.940
to indicate that this
is a coupon.

00:08:02.940 --> 00:08:07.780
Kind of like on google.com, you
see the text ads in search

00:08:07.780 --> 00:08:09.350
results on a yellow
background.

00:08:09.350 --> 00:08:10.420
This would be kind of similar.

00:08:10.420 --> 00:08:14.830
So you present a visual theme
throughout that says, hey,

00:08:14.830 --> 00:08:17.760
blue is advertising,
or blue is coupons.

00:08:17.760 --> 00:08:19.440
And green is your stuff.

00:08:19.440 --> 00:08:22.220
So it's kind of one of the
ways to think about that.

00:08:22.220 --> 00:08:23.570
And the last thing I want to
point out on this screen

00:08:23.570 --> 00:08:25.680
before-- if you guys
want to chime in--

00:08:25.680 --> 00:08:27.240
is this bar at the top.

00:08:27.240 --> 00:08:29.920
And this is something that
Adam and I talked about

00:08:29.920 --> 00:08:31.720
beforehand, and Nick
as well, I believe.

00:08:31.720 --> 00:08:35.200
Is really how do you present
adding items or

00:08:35.200 --> 00:08:36.870
searching for stuff?

00:08:36.870 --> 00:08:38.780
And in this case, searching and
adding is really part of

00:08:38.780 --> 00:08:40.280
the same flow.

00:08:40.280 --> 00:08:42.730
And we decided to make it kind
of a first-class citizen

00:08:42.730 --> 00:08:44.300
rather than an action button.

00:08:44.300 --> 00:08:49.200
We've put it in line at the
very top of the list.

00:08:49.200 --> 00:08:51.000
So that's all I want
to mention.

00:08:51.000 --> 00:08:53.860
Adam, I remember you had
thoughts on search and add.

00:08:53.860 --> 00:08:55.050
You want to talk about
some alternatives?

00:08:55.050 --> 00:08:55.850
ADAM KOCH: Yeah.

00:08:55.850 --> 00:08:59.860
I guess one thing I wanted to
talk about was you can always

00:08:59.860 --> 00:09:01.010
have an action item.

00:09:01.010 --> 00:09:03.360
But if the action is really
important, you can put it in

00:09:03.360 --> 00:09:05.980
line like Roman has
shown here.

00:09:05.980 --> 00:09:08.820
But I guess if you did want to,
you could move that Add or

00:09:08.820 --> 00:09:12.770
Search box back into the action
bar as an action item,

00:09:12.770 --> 00:09:15.430
and maybe trigger the sort of
contextual search that shows

00:09:15.430 --> 00:09:17.880
directly in the action
bar itself.

00:09:17.880 --> 00:09:21.020
So that's just an alternative,
totally up to the designer of

00:09:21.020 --> 00:09:22.310
the app as to how they
actually want

00:09:22.310 --> 00:09:23.020
to implement this.

00:09:23.020 --> 00:09:25.260
ROMAN NURIK: Yeah, almost an
expanding search view.

00:09:25.260 --> 00:09:27.986
But maybe it's an expanding
add view.

00:09:27.986 --> 00:09:30.350
ADAM KOCH: An interesting
approach.

00:09:30.350 --> 00:09:32.920
ROMAN NURIK: In one of the later
apps, Nick will talk

00:09:32.920 --> 00:09:37.100
about some similar ways in which
he approached this in

00:09:37.100 --> 00:09:38.040
Out of Milk.

00:09:38.040 --> 00:09:39.710
But anyway, let's move on to
the next screen, in the

00:09:39.710 --> 00:09:41.560
interest of time.

00:09:41.560 --> 00:09:43.130
So the next screen-- again,
since this is about the

00:09:43.130 --> 00:09:46.580
contextual action bar, this is
just briefly showing that--

00:09:46.580 --> 00:09:49.750
let's say I wanted to
immediately take action on

00:09:49.750 --> 00:09:51.100
three or four of those items.

00:09:51.100 --> 00:09:53.865
I can just long press
to start selection.

00:09:53.865 --> 00:09:55.380
And that pops up the contextual

00:09:55.380 --> 00:09:56.960
action bar at the top.

00:09:56.960 --> 00:10:00.750
And then keep single touching
different items in my list to

00:10:00.750 --> 00:10:03.040
add or remove from
the selection.

00:10:03.040 --> 00:10:05.180
And then take action on
that entire selection.

00:10:05.180 --> 00:10:08.200
So in this case, I've selected
Hoegaarden and Macallan.

00:10:08.200 --> 00:10:10.330
Hopefully I've spelled
Macallan right--

00:10:10.330 --> 00:10:11.320
Hoegaarden and Macallan.

00:10:11.320 --> 00:10:13.970
And then let's say I've gone
ahead and bought those items

00:10:13.970 --> 00:10:14.770
at the store.

00:10:14.770 --> 00:10:18.600
I could just select both and
press Mark Purchased.

00:10:18.600 --> 00:10:20.800
to take action immediately
on those two items.

00:10:23.620 --> 00:10:27.380
In the next screen, this is an
example of that dropdown.

00:10:27.380 --> 00:10:28.440
And this is kind
of interesting.

00:10:28.440 --> 00:10:33.660
This is something that we took
a few liberties with.

00:10:33.660 --> 00:10:35.320
Dropdown/Spinner navigation--

00:10:35.320 --> 00:10:39.160
usually, you just see the items
which you're switching

00:10:39.160 --> 00:10:40.370
between, right?

00:10:40.370 --> 00:10:43.740
So in a normal case, you'd see
Grocery Store, Bakery, or Any

00:10:43.740 --> 00:10:46.400
Store, meaning all
of the above.

00:10:46.400 --> 00:10:52.330
But in this case, since this
is the single place where

00:10:52.330 --> 00:10:54.980
users see their list
of stores--

00:10:54.980 --> 00:10:58.220
this is the most visible place
in the app where they see

00:10:58.220 --> 00:10:59.520
their list of stores.

00:10:59.520 --> 00:11:04.060
Let's make it easy to also then
take action on that list,

00:11:04.060 --> 00:11:07.010
to then maybe add a store to
that list right from here.

00:11:07.010 --> 00:11:09.735
This is something that Ian
mentioned last week on "The

00:11:09.735 --> 00:11:13.450
App Clinic." It's a missed
opportunity if you see a list

00:11:13.450 --> 00:11:16.280
of things, and you know want to
add one, but you then can't

00:11:16.280 --> 00:11:16.970
figure out how to do it.

00:11:16.970 --> 00:11:19.090
So this way, it makes
it very obvious.

00:11:19.090 --> 00:11:23.150
It's a slight deviation from
the standard pattern, but I

00:11:23.150 --> 00:11:27.130
personally feel that it's a
fairly reasonable deviation.

00:11:27.130 --> 00:11:29.590
And then the other thing is that
there's also Favorites

00:11:29.590 --> 00:11:30.420
and History.

00:11:30.420 --> 00:11:32.470
And to navigate to those items--
