00:19:30.330 --> 00:19:31.650
done, for example.

00:19:31.650 --> 00:19:35.260
And if you long press on an
item, it then puts a score

00:19:35.260 --> 00:19:36.690
through it and moves
it to the bottom,

00:19:36.690 --> 00:19:37.800
denoting that it's done.

00:19:37.800 --> 00:19:40.830
So you kind of have
these two levels.

00:19:40.830 --> 00:19:42.410
So if it's an item on the list,
then you can have it

00:19:42.410 --> 00:19:43.270
scored through.

00:19:43.270 --> 00:19:44.720
Or then you can actually
delete it to

00:19:44.720 --> 00:19:46.940
totally remove it.

00:19:46.940 --> 00:19:49.580
There's many permutations of
state which an item can be in.

00:19:49.580 --> 00:19:52.290
And because of this-- if you
just close the Overflow menu.

00:19:52.290 --> 00:19:53.940
I don't think we've got a
screenshot of it here.

00:19:53.940 --> 00:19:56.680
But if you do, there is a
plethora of options there.

00:19:56.680 --> 00:19:58.620
You actually have to scroll
it on a Galaxy Nexus.

00:19:58.620 --> 00:20:02.947
There's that many overflow
options, which I found to be a

00:20:02.947 --> 00:20:04.438
bit-- kind of overloaded me.

00:20:08.100 --> 00:20:10.450
ROMAN NURIK: This is kind of
against the concept of direct

00:20:10.450 --> 00:20:14.400
manipulation, which is one of
the design principles in a

00:20:14.400 --> 00:20:15.730
design guide.

00:20:15.730 --> 00:20:17.180
Items should be manipulable.

00:20:17.180 --> 00:20:19.940
You should be able to touch
them, to interact with them.

00:20:19.940 --> 00:20:23.850
Rather than choosing actions
somewhere else to do things

00:20:23.850 --> 00:20:27.490
like trigger selection, or
Select All, Deselect All.

00:20:27.490 --> 00:20:31.550
Anything like that should really
be more contextual.

00:20:31.550 --> 00:20:34.550
And in general, if you look at
just for long press, I think

00:20:34.550 --> 00:20:37.980
that's particularly egregious
in this case, where we've

00:20:37.980 --> 00:20:40.840
tried to standardize on
what long press means.

00:20:40.840 --> 00:20:42.880
And really, it means
selection.

00:20:42.880 --> 00:20:46.370
It triggers selection and then
potentially showing actions on

00:20:46.370 --> 00:20:47.500
your selection.

00:20:47.500 --> 00:20:52.450
So using it for anything else
like marking an item as

00:20:52.450 --> 00:20:56.330
complete, it's kind of beyond
what the standards are.

00:20:56.330 --> 00:20:58.970
And it's just another thing
that users have to learn.

