And then tuck the less used
and much smaller set of

00:23:00.560 --> 00:23:03.230
alternative actions under
the Overflow.

00:23:03.230 --> 00:23:05.520
So we've also changed up the
interaction a little

00:23:05.520 --> 00:23:06.260
bit here, as well.

00:23:06.260 --> 00:23:10.640
You can see I've placed some
check boxes next to the items,

00:23:10.640 --> 00:23:14.980
which allow you to go into
a selection mode.

00:23:14.980 --> 00:23:17.230
So I've actually kind of flipped
the concept or changed

00:23:17.230 --> 00:23:20.700
the concept a little bit and
got rid of the idea of a

00:23:20.700 --> 00:23:23.750
semi-struck-through done state,
and just gone straight

00:23:23.750 --> 00:23:24.850
to a dismissed state.

00:23:24.850 --> 00:23:28.420
So I decided to use the Swipe
to Dismiss pattern that's

00:23:28.420 --> 00:23:32.510
we're seeing gaining traction
these days as the way

00:23:32.510 --> 00:23:33.170
to mark items off.

00:23:33.170 --> 00:23:35.590
So this is speaking to Roman's
point about direct

00:23:35.590 --> 00:23:37.930
manipulation of your data being
much more satisfying.

00:23:37.930 --> 00:23:39.260
So what you can actually do--

00:23:39.260 --> 00:23:40.460
yeah, here we go-- is
you can swipe--

00:23:40.460 --> 00:23:42.040
ROMAN NURIK: This is like Swipe
to Complete, rather than

00:23:42.040 --> 00:23:42.660
Swipe to Delete.

00:23:42.660 --> 00:23:45.240
I wrote Swipe to Delete here,
but it's like Swipe to mark as

00:23:45.240 --> 00:23:46.230
completed, basically, right?

00:23:46.230 --> 00:23:47.790
NICK BUTCHER: Yeah.

00:23:47.790 --> 00:23:50.080
So this is a bit of a change
to the pattern.

00:23:50.080 --> 00:23:53.335
Because I guess in the old way,
you would long press it.

00:23:53.335 --> 00:23:55.240
It'd be struck through, so it'd
still be able to get it

00:23:55.240 --> 00:23:55.710
back quickly.

00:23:55.710 --> 00:23:58.660
So it's a way to give you that
safety net, that way to easily

00:23:58.660 --> 00:24:01.450
recover any data that you've
marked as complete.

00:24:01.450 --> 00:24:02.890
We've also used a
new pattern--

00:24:02.890 --> 00:24:05.130
an emerging pattern--
of the Undo.

00:24:05.130 --> 00:24:09.360
So when you swipe away an item
to say it's done, we actually

00:24:09.360 --> 00:24:12.690
temporarily showed this Undo
option in line where it was.

00:24:12.690 --> 00:24:15.320
The idea here being that until
you interact with the screen

00:24:15.320 --> 00:24:17.110
again, this will stay there.

00:24:17.110 --> 00:24:20.880
So it gives you this chance to
say, oh, actually I checked

00:24:20.880 --> 00:24:22.930
the wrong item, whatever.

00:24:22.930 --> 00:24:24.730
But the minute you start
scrolling or touching another

00:24:24.730 --> 00:24:27.730
item, the idea is that
this would close up.

00:24:32.220 --> 00:24:34.230
ROMAN NURIK: The next one-- the
quick return-- you want to

00:24:34.230 --> 00:24:35.015
talk about that?

00:24:35.015 --> 00:24:37.310
NICK BUTCHER: Yeah,
absolutely.

00:24:37.310 --> 00:24:40.070
So this is to go with the idea
that we've made Add this

00:24:40.070 --> 00:24:41.200
really prominent item.

00:24:41.200 --> 00:24:45.440
But we wanted to cope with the
case that you might be having

00:24:45.440 --> 00:24:47.390
too many layers of
items at the top.

00:24:47.390 --> 00:24:48.280
You have an action bar.

00:24:48.280 --> 00:24:50.045
Sometimes you might have
tabs, if you had an

00:24:50.045 --> 00:24:51.570
