00:24:51.570 --> 00:24:53.335
You end up running out of room,
especially if you're in,

00:24:53.335 --> 00:24:56.170
say, landscape view, where you
have less vertical space.

00:24:56.170 --> 00:24:59.330
So I'm using here a pattern
which we've been dubbing Quick

00:24:59.330 --> 00:25:02.780
Return, which I think is a
really, really cool way too

00:25:02.780 --> 00:25:03.970
handle that problem.

00:25:03.970 --> 00:25:05.900
So the idea here is if you
had a lot of items--

00:25:05.900 --> 00:25:07.640
so here I'm making lasagna.

00:25:07.640 --> 00:25:11.300
And I've got a lot of
items in my list.

00:25:11.300 --> 00:25:15.590
As they scroll away, the Add
button, the horizontal bar,

00:25:15.590 --> 00:25:17.160
will scroll out of view.

00:25:17.160 --> 00:25:20.440
But the minute they start
dragging back down, it'll jump

00:25:20.440 --> 00:25:22.330
right back in and be
this floating item.

00:25:22.330 --> 00:25:25.600
So what this really does, it
lets you maximize the amount

00:25:25.600 --> 00:25:28.840
of space you have to play with
in the screen and show the

00:25:28.840 --> 00:25:29.430
items on the list.

00:25:29.430 --> 00:25:30.820
So if you're searching through
the list, looking for a

00:25:30.820 --> 00:25:33.970
